<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="468" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,679,1677]" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,417,788,813]" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">Revised diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Salgado &amp; Ruiz, 2017" authorityName="Salgado &amp; Ruiz" authorityYear="2017" box="[424,940,788,813]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Amphidraus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="17" pageNumber="468" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caxiuanan">
<emphasis box="[424,685,788,812]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">Amphidraus caxiuanan</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Salgado, A. &amp; Ruiz, G. R." box="[691,940,788,813]" pageId="17" pageNumber="468" pagination="401 - 437" refId="ref8937" refString="Salgado, A. &amp; Ruiz, G. R. S (2017) Ten new species of Amphidraus Simon, 1900 (Araneae: Salticidae: Euophryini) and three new combinations. Zootaxa, 4312 (3), 401 - 437. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4312.3.1" type="journal article" year="2017">Salgado &amp; Ruiz, 2017</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Salgado &amp; Ruiz, 2019" authorityName="Salgado &amp; Ruiz" authorityYear="2019" box="[995,1141,788,812]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Amphidraus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="17" pageNumber="468" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="manauara" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[995,1141,788,812]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">A. manauara</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1148,1238,788,813]" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1148,1238,788,813]" pageId="17" pageNumber="468" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
have the embolic disc with one long, prolaterally projected, distal process (dPED) with rounded tip, and one short, ventrally projected ventral process (vPED) (
<figureCitation box="[546,656,860,885]" captionStart="FIGURE 17" captionStartId="18.[151,250,1883,1905]" captionTargetBox="[157,1401,276,1828]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[151,1436,248,1861]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 17. Amphidraus manauara sp. nov. A–C left male palp (A ventral; B dorsal; C retrolateral); D epigyne/vulva, cleared, ventral. Abbreviations: cc, cymbial conductor; cd, copulatory duct; co, copulatory opening; Cy, cymbium; dPED, distal process on embolic disc; e, embolus shaft; ed, embolic disc; ef, embolic filament; fd, fertilization duct; gl, gland; po, coupling pocket; RTA, retrolateral tibial apophysis; RvTA, retroventral tibial apophysis; S, spermatheca; T, tegulum; TL, tegular lobe; vPED, ventral process on embolic disc." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2601378/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">Figs 17A</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[669,719,860,884]" captionStart="FIGURE 19" captionStartId="20.[151,250,1557,1579]" captionTargetBox="[171,1416,199,1524]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[151,1436,173,1536]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURE 19. Comparison of male palpal structures in Amphidraus spp. A–B, E left male palp of A. manauara sp. nov. (A ventral; B cymbium, dorsal; E retrolateral, bulb removed). C–D, F–G left male palp of A. caxiuanan Salgado &amp; Ruiz, 2017 (C holotype from Melgaço, ventral; D same, cymbium, dorsal; G same, retrolateral, bulb removed; F specimen from Oriximiná, retrolateral, bulb removed. Abbreviations: Cy, cymbium; RTA, retrolateral tibial apophysis; RvTA, retroventral tibial apophysis; T, tegulum." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2601384/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">19C</figureCitation>
); also, the same pattern of tibial apophyses: the RvTA is short and rounded and the RTA emerges from retrodorsal portion of tibia, being curved and projected to the apex of palp (
<figureCitation box="[159,243,932,957]" captionStart="FIGURE 19" captionStartId="20.[151,250,1557,1579]" captionTargetBox="[171,1416,199,1524]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[151,1436,173,1536]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURE 19. Comparison of male palpal structures in Amphidraus spp. A–B, E left male palp of A. manauara sp. nov. (A ventral; B cymbium, dorsal; E retrolateral, bulb removed). C–D, F–G left male palp of A. caxiuanan Salgado &amp; Ruiz, 2017 (C holotype from Melgaço, ventral; D same, cymbium, dorsal; G same, retrolateral, bulb removed; F specimen from Oriximiná, retrolateral, bulb removed. Abbreviations: Cy, cymbium; RTA, retrolateral tibial apophysis; RvTA, retroventral tibial apophysis; T, tegulum." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2601384/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">Figs 19</figureCitation>
E–G); proximal dorso-prolateral portion of cymbium is prominent in both species, and there is a proximal retro-dorsal cavity on cymbium (
<figureCitation box="[525,632,967,992]" captionStart="FIGURE 17" captionStartId="18.[151,250,1883,1905]" captionTargetBox="[157,1401,276,1828]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[151,1436,248,1861]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 17. Amphidraus manauara sp. nov. A–C left male palp (A ventral; B dorsal; C retrolateral); D epigyne/vulva, cleared, ventral. Abbreviations: cc, cymbial conductor; cd, copulatory duct; co, copulatory opening; Cy, cymbium; dPED, distal process on embolic disc; e, embolus shaft; ed, embolic disc; ef, embolic filament; fd, fertilization duct; gl, gland; po, coupling pocket; RTA, retrolateral tibial apophysis; RvTA, retroventral tibial apophysis; S, spermatheca; T, tegulum; TL, tegular lobe; vPED, ventral process on embolic disc." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2601378/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">Figs 17B</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[646,760,968,992]" captionStart="FIGURE 19" captionStartId="20.[151,250,1557,1579]" captionTargetBox="[171,1416,199,1524]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[151,1436,173,1536]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURE 19. Comparison of male palpal structures in Amphidraus spp. A–B, E left male palp of A. manauara sp. nov. (A ventral; B cymbium, dorsal; E retrolateral, bulb removed). C–D, F–G left male palp of A. caxiuanan Salgado &amp; Ruiz, 2017 (C holotype from Melgaço, ventral; D same, cymbium, dorsal; G same, retrolateral, bulb removed; F specimen from Oriximiná, retrolateral, bulb removed. Abbreviations: Cy, cymbium; RTA, retrolateral tibial apophysis; RvTA, retroventral tibial apophysis; T, tegulum." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2601384/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">19B, 19D</figureCitation>
). However, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Salgado &amp; Ruiz" authorityYear="2017" box="[898,1160,968,992]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Amphidraus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="17" pageNumber="468" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caxiuanan">
<emphasis box="[898,1160,968,992]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">Amphidraus caxiuanan</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished by having a longer proximal dorso-prolateral projection of cymbium (
<figureCitation box="[904,1072,1004,1029]" captionStart="FIGURE 19" captionStartId="20.[151,250,1557,1579]" captionTargetBox="[171,1416,199,1524]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[151,1436,173,1536]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURE 19. Comparison of male palpal structures in Amphidraus spp. A–B, E left male palp of A. manauara sp. nov. (A ventral; B cymbium, dorsal; E retrolateral, bulb removed). C–D, F–G left male palp of A. caxiuanan Salgado &amp; Ruiz, 2017 (C holotype from Melgaço, ventral; D same, cymbium, dorsal; G same, retrolateral, bulb removed; F specimen from Oriximiná, retrolateral, bulb removed. Abbreviations: Cy, cymbium; RTA, retrolateral tibial apophysis; RvTA, retroventral tibial apophysis; T, tegulum." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2601384/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">Figs 19B, 19D</figureCitation>
) and longer RTA (
<figureCitation box="[1283,1367,1004,1029]" captionStart="FIGURE 19" captionStartId="20.[151,250,1557,1579]" captionTargetBox="[171,1416,199,1524]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[151,1436,173,1536]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURE 19. Comparison of male palpal structures in Amphidraus spp. A–B, E left male palp of A. manauara sp. nov. (A ventral; B cymbium, dorsal; E retrolateral, bulb removed). C–D, F–G left male palp of A. caxiuanan Salgado &amp; Ruiz, 2017 (C holotype from Melgaço, ventral; D same, cymbium, dorsal; G same, retrolateral, bulb removed; F specimen from Oriximiná, retrolateral, bulb removed. Abbreviations: Cy, cymbium; RTA, retrolateral tibial apophysis; RvTA, retroventral tibial apophysis; T, tegulum." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2601384/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">Figs 19</figureCitation>
E–G). Moreover, the embolus shaft and the embolic filament are longer in proportion to the embolic disc in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Salgado &amp; Ruiz" authorityYear="2017" box="[1288,1436,1040,1063]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Amphidraus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="17" pageNumber="468" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caxiuanan">
<emphasis box="[1288,1436,1040,1063]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">A. caxiuanan</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[159,328,1076,1101]" captionStart="FIGURE 19" captionStartId="20.[151,250,1557,1579]" captionTargetBox="[171,1416,199,1524]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[151,1436,173,1536]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURE 19. Comparison of male palpal structures in Amphidraus spp. A–B, E left male palp of A. manauara sp. nov. (A ventral; B cymbium, dorsal; E retrolateral, bulb removed). C–D, F–G left male palp of A. caxiuanan Salgado &amp; Ruiz, 2017 (C holotype from Melgaço, ventral; D same, cymbium, dorsal; G same, retrolateral, bulb removed; F specimen from Oriximiná, retrolateral, bulb removed. Abbreviations: Cy, cymbium; RTA, retrolateral tibial apophysis; RvTA, retroventral tibial apophysis; T, tegulum." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2601384/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">Figs 19A, 19C</figureCitation>
). The female of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Salgado &amp; Ruiz" authorityYear="2017" box="[511,659,1076,1100]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Amphidraus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="17" pageNumber="468" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caxiuanan">
<emphasis box="[511,659,1076,1100]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">A. caxiuanan</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is still unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="468" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,679,1677]" box="[199,667,1111,1136]" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1111,1136]" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">Description.</emphasis>
See 
<bibRefCitation author="Salgado, A. &amp; Ruiz, G. R." box="[399,662,1111,1136]" pageId="17" pageNumber="468" pagination="401 - 437" refId="ref8937" refString="Salgado, A. &amp; Ruiz, G. R. S (2017) Ten new species of Amphidraus Simon, 1900 (Araneae: Salticidae: Euophryini) and three new combinations. Zootaxa, 4312 (3), 401 - 437. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4312.3.1" type="journal article" year="2017">Salgado &amp; Ruiz (2017)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,679,1677]" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,319,1148,1173]" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">Variation.</emphasis>
Based on comparisons between the type specimen of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Salgado &amp; Ruiz" authorityYear="2017" box="[922,1070,1148,1172]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Amphidraus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="17" pageNumber="468" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caxiuanan">
<emphasis box="[922,1070,1148,1172]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">A. caxiuanan</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Melgaço, 
<collectingRegion box="[1250,1303,1148,1172]" country="Brazil" name="Para" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">Pará</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1313,1384,1148,1173]" name="Brazil" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, and this new male from Oriximiná, 
<collectingRegion box="[514,567,1184,1208]" country="Brazil" name="Para" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">Pará</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[580,648,1183,1208]" name="Brazil" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(about 
<quantity box="[738,825,1183,1208]" metricMagnitude="5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.5" pageId="17" pageNumber="468" unit="km" value="550.0">550 km</quantity>
from the type locality; 
<figureCitation box="[1098,1183,1183,1208]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="21.[151,250,1482,1504]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,629,1460]" captionTargetId="figure@21.[151,1436,629,1460]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURE 20. Map of northern Brazil showing records of Amphidraus caxiuanan and A. manauara. White lines represent the borders of Brazilian states. Map modified from Google Earth ®. Blue line between Manaus and Melgaço represents the Amazon River." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2601386/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">Fig. 20</figureCitation>
), we observed several similarities, including in tibial apophyses and especially in the embolic disc, which made us refrain from describing a new species from Oriximiná. That male is herein recognized as being a variant form of 
<emphasis box="[1190,1349,1256,1279]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Salgado &amp; Ruiz" authorityYear="2017" box="[1190,1344,1256,1279]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Amphidraus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="17" pageNumber="468" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caxiuanan">A. caxiuanan</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
Hence, palpal variation within the species is summarized as follows (
<figureCitation box="[839,922,1292,1317]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="19.[151,250,1848,1870]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1818]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[151,1436,193,1826]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 18. Morphological variation in Amphidraus caxiuanan Salgado &amp; Ruiz, 2017. A–D holotype from Melgaço, Pará (A male, dorsal; B left palp, ventral; C retrolateral; D dorsal). E–H specimen from Oriximiná, Pará (E male, dorsal; F left palp, ventral; G retrolateral; H dorsal). Abbreviations: cc, cymbial conductor; dPED, distal process on embolic disc; e, embolus shaft; ef, embolic filament; RTA, retrolateral tibial apophysis; RvTA, retroventral tibial apophysis; TL, tegular lobe; vPED, ventral process on embolic disc. Black arrow in D shows dorso-prolateral, proximal cymbial projection." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2601380/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">Figs 18</figureCitation>
B–D, 18F–H, 19C–D, 19F–G): the RTA has a slight (
<figureCitation box="[228,332,1327,1352]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="19.[151,250,1848,1870]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1818]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[151,1436,193,1826]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 18. Morphological variation in Amphidraus caxiuanan Salgado &amp; Ruiz, 2017. A–D holotype from Melgaço, Pará (A male, dorsal; B left palp, ventral; C retrolateral; D dorsal). E–H specimen from Oriximiná, Pará (E male, dorsal; F left palp, ventral; G retrolateral; H dorsal). Abbreviations: cc, cymbial conductor; dPED, distal process on embolic disc; e, embolus shaft; ef, embolic filament; RTA, retrolateral tibial apophysis; RvTA, retroventral tibial apophysis; TL, tegular lobe; vPED, ventral process on embolic disc. Black arrow in D shows dorso-prolateral, proximal cymbial projection." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2601380/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">Figs 18G</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[343,388,1328,1352]" captionStart="FIGURE 19" captionStartId="20.[151,250,1557,1579]" captionTargetBox="[171,1416,199,1524]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[151,1436,173,1536]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURE 19. Comparison of male palpal structures in Amphidraus spp. A–B, E left male palp of A. manauara sp. nov. (A ventral; B cymbium, dorsal; E retrolateral, bulb removed). C–D, F–G left male palp of A. caxiuanan Salgado &amp; Ruiz, 2017 (C holotype from Melgaço, ventral; D same, cymbium, dorsal; G same, retrolateral, bulb removed; F specimen from Oriximiná, retrolateral, bulb removed. Abbreviations: Cy, cymbium; RTA, retrolateral tibial apophysis; RvTA, retroventral tibial apophysis; T, tegulum." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2601384/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">19F</figureCitation>
) or accentuated curvature (
<figureCitation box="[693,800,1327,1352]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="19.[151,250,1848,1870]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1818]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[151,1436,193,1826]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 18. Morphological variation in Amphidraus caxiuanan Salgado &amp; Ruiz, 2017. A–D holotype from Melgaço, Pará (A male, dorsal; B left palp, ventral; C retrolateral; D dorsal). E–H specimen from Oriximiná, Pará (E male, dorsal; F left palp, ventral; G retrolateral; H dorsal). Abbreviations: cc, cymbial conductor; dPED, distal process on embolic disc; e, embolus shaft; ef, embolic filament; RTA, retrolateral tibial apophysis; RvTA, retroventral tibial apophysis; TL, tegular lobe; vPED, ventral process on embolic disc. Black arrow in D shows dorso-prolateral, proximal cymbial projection." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2601380/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">Figs 18C</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[811,863,1328,1352]" captionStart="FIGURE 19" captionStartId="20.[151,250,1557,1579]" captionTargetBox="[171,1416,199,1524]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[151,1436,173,1536]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURE 19. Comparison of male palpal structures in Amphidraus spp. A–B, E left male palp of A. manauara sp. nov. (A ventral; B cymbium, dorsal; E retrolateral, bulb removed). C–D, F–G left male palp of A. caxiuanan Salgado &amp; Ruiz, 2017 (C holotype from Melgaço, ventral; D same, cymbium, dorsal; G same, retrolateral, bulb removed; F specimen from Oriximiná, retrolateral, bulb removed. Abbreviations: Cy, cymbium; RTA, retrolateral tibial apophysis; RvTA, retroventral tibial apophysis; T, tegulum." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2601384/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">19G</figureCitation>
); the dorso-prolateral, proximal cymbial projection varies in length (
<figureCitation box="[355,536,1364,1389]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="19.[151,250,1848,1870]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1818]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[151,1436,193,1826]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 18. Morphological variation in Amphidraus caxiuanan Salgado &amp; Ruiz, 2017. A–D holotype from Melgaço, Pará (A male, dorsal; B left palp, ventral; C retrolateral; D dorsal). E–H specimen from Oriximiná, Pará (E male, dorsal; F left palp, ventral; G retrolateral; H dorsal). Abbreviations: cc, cymbial conductor; dPED, distal process on embolic disc; e, embolus shaft; ef, embolic filament; RTA, retrolateral tibial apophysis; RvTA, retroventral tibial apophysis; TL, tegular lobe; vPED, ventral process on embolic disc. Black arrow in D shows dorso-prolateral, proximal cymbial projection." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2601380/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">Figs 18D, 18H</figureCitation>
); RTA length is also variable (
<figureCitation box="[909,998,1364,1389]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="19.[151,250,1848,1870]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1818]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[151,1436,193,1826]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 18. Morphological variation in Amphidraus caxiuanan Salgado &amp; Ruiz, 2017. A–D holotype from Melgaço, Pará (A male, dorsal; B left palp, ventral; C retrolateral; D dorsal). E–H specimen from Oriximiná, Pará (E male, dorsal; F left palp, ventral; G retrolateral; H dorsal). Abbreviations: cc, cymbial conductor; dPED, distal process on embolic disc; e, embolus shaft; ef, embolic filament; RTA, retrolateral tibial apophysis; RvTA, retroventral tibial apophysis; TL, tegular lobe; vPED, ventral process on embolic disc. Black arrow in D shows dorso-prolateral, proximal cymbial projection." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2601380/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">Figs 18</figureCitation>
C–D, 18G–H, 19F–G). However, the proportions of these structures in the male from Oriximiná are intermediate when comparing the 
<typeStatus box="[1271,1369,1399,1424]" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Salgado &amp; Ruiz" authorityYear="2017" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Amphidraus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="17" pageNumber="468" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caxiuanan">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">A. caxiuanan</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the 
<typeStatus box="[365,463,1436,1461]" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Salgado &amp; Ruiz" authorityYear="2019" box="[501,648,1436,1460]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Amphidraus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="17" pageNumber="468" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="manauara">
<emphasis box="[501,648,1436,1460]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">A. manauara</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(whose type locality is about 
<quantity box="[988,1073,1436,1461]" metricMagnitude="5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" pageId="17" pageNumber="468" unit="km" value="450.0">450 km</quantity>
away from Oriximiná; 
<figureCitation box="[1340,1423,1436,1461]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="21.[151,250,1482,1504]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,629,1460]" captionTargetId="figure@21.[151,1436,629,1460]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURE 20. Map of northern Brazil showing records of Amphidraus caxiuanan and A. manauara. White lines represent the borders of Brazilian states. Map modified from Google Earth ®. Blue line between Manaus and Melgaço represents the Amazon River." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2601386/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">Fig. 20</figureCitation>
), which could indicate a cline across the Amazon River. Nevertheless, the embolic disc of the male palp of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Salgado &amp; Ruiz" authorityYear="2019" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Amphidraus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="17" pageNumber="468" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="manauara">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">A. manauara</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is different enough to convince us to describe it as a new species (see diagnoses above).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="468" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,679,1677]" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,1543,1568]" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">Distribution.</emphasis>
Known only from the state of 
<collectingRegion box="[694,747,1544,1568]" country="Brazil" name="Para" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">Pará</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[758,826,1543,1568]" name="Brazil" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[841,925,1543,1568]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="21.[151,250,1482,1504]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,629,1460]" captionTargetId="figure@21.[151,1436,629,1460]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURE 20. Map of northern Brazil showing records of Amphidraus caxiuanan and A. manauara. White lines represent the borders of Brazilian states. Map modified from Google Earth ®. Blue line between Manaus and Melgaço represents the Amazon River." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2601386/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">Fig. 20</figureCitation>
). It is worth mentioning that, if the specimens from Oriximiná and Melgaço are indeed conspecific, this small species of jumping spider occurs in preserved forests on both margins of the old Amazon River, which is between two and eight kilometers wide in that portion of South America. This provides evidence for the high ability of dispersal present in this species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
